Definition: A chief executive officer (CEO) or managing director is the top-ranking corporate officer responsible for the management of an organization.
Career Pathway: Managing Director, Executive Director, Chief Operating Officer, President, Chief Executive Officer
Competencies: Determining objectives, strategies, policies and programs for organisations,Providing overall direction and management to organisations,Authorising material, human and financial resources to implement organisational policies and programs,Monitoring and evaluating performance of organisations against organisational objectives and strategies,Consulting with senior subordinate staff and reviewing recommendations and reports,Preparing, or arranging for the preparation of, reports, budgets and forecasts and presenting them to governing bodies,Representing the organisation at official occasions, in negotiations, at conventions, seminars, public hearings and forums, and liaising between areas of responsibility,Selecting and approving the selection of senior staff,Ensuring the organisation complies with company laws and other relevant legislation
Core Skills: Financial Management, Strategic Planning, Data Analysis, Business Analysis, Operations Analysis
Certifications (External): Certified Chief Executive Officer (CCEO), Australian Institute of Company Directors (AICD) Company Directors Course, Harvard Business School Online Executive Education Certificate, Stanford Graduate School of Business Executive Program, Chartered Management Consultant (ChMC), Certified Manager (CM)
Technologies: CEO Software, AI-enabled software platforms, Business intelligence tools, Data analytics, Project management software, Cloud computing, Agentic AI
Soft Skills: Communication, Emotional Intelligence, Good Judgment, Conflict Resolution, Adaptability

Definition: A general manager is responsible for overseeing a department or company operations, managing staff, budgets, and marketing, with the goal of improving efficiency and profitability.
Career Pathway: Assistant General Manager, General Manager, Chief Executive Officer, President
Competencies: Planning policy, and setting standards and objectives for organisations,Providing day-to-day direction and management of organisations, and directing and endorsing policy to fulfil objectives, achieve specific goals, and maximise profit and efficiency,Assessing changing situations and responding accordingly by issuing commands and directives to subordinate staff,Consulting with immediate subordinates and departmental heads on matters such as methods of operation, equipment requirements, finance, sales and human resources,Authorising the funding of major policy implementation programs,Representing the organisation at official occasions, in negotiations, at conventions, seminars, public hearings and forums, and liaising between areas of responsibility,Preparing, or arranging for the preparation of, reports, budgets and forecasts, and presenting them to governing bodies,Selecting and managing the performance of senior staff,May undertake responsibility for some or all of accounting, sales, marketing, human resources and other specialist operations
Core Skills: Financial management, budgeting, forecasting, cost control, operations management
Certifications (External): PMP, Certified Manager (CM), Certified in Management (CIM)
Technologies: Project Management Software, Customer Relationship Management (CRM) Systems, Business Intelligence (BI) Tools, Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) Software, Communication and Collaboration Tools, Financial Management Software, Marketing Automation Platforms
Soft Skills: Leadership, Effective Communication, Emotional Intelligence, Strategic Thinking, Problem-Solving

Definition: Develop, introduce, or enact laws and statutes at the local, tribal, state, or federal level.
Career Pathway: Staff Assistant, Legislative Assistant, Deputy Legislative Counsel (or similar title, e.g., Performance Auditor, Lead Auditor), Principal Deputy (or similar supervisory/management role, e.g., Audit Supervisor, Audit Manager), Leadership Positions (e.g., President of the Senate, Speaker of the House)
Competencies: Developing national, state, territory or local government policy, and formulating, amending and repealing legislation and by-laws ,Helping constituents with a range of problems particularly with regard to matters concerning government and local agencies ,Investigating matters of concern to the public and to particular persons and groups ,Introducing proposals for government action and representing public and electoral interests ,Issuing policy directions to government departments and exercising control over local government authorities ,Attending community functions and meetings of local groups to provide service to the community, gauge public opinion and provide information on government plans ,May serve as a member on parliamentary committees and inquiries ,May present petitions on behalf of concerned groups
Core Skills: Legislative knowledge, Senate knowledge, Political judgement, Analyzing proposed legislation, Formulating positions and strategies
Certifications (External): CPA Parliamentary Service Professional Development Certificate, Certificate in Parliamentary Procedure, Certificate in Legislative Drafting, Public Policy and Administration Certificate, Executive Certificate in Legislative Affairs, Advanced Diploma of Government, Graduate Certificate in Governance and Public Policy
Technologies: Data integrity, system security, disaster recovery procedures, IT budgets, IT contracts, procurement, website development
Soft Skills: Interpersonal skills, Communication, Adaptability, Initiative, Organization

Definition: Aquaculture farmers breed and rear fish or shellfish in controlled environments like ponds, tanks, cages, or nets, primarily for food.
Career Pathway: Internship/Apprenticeship, Entry-level job on an aquaculture farm, Aquaculture Farmer, Farm Manager/Supervisor, Aquaculture Consultant/Business Owner/Researcher
Competencies: Planning and coordinating the operation of hatcheries to produce fish fry, seed oysters, crayfish, marron and prawns taking into account environmental and market factors,Monitoring the environment to maintain optimal growing conditions,Identifying and controlling environmental toxins and diseases,Monitoring stock growth rates to determine when to harvest,Transporting fish, crayfish, marron, prawns and sticks of seed oysters to new tanks, ponds, cages and floating net pens,Directing and overseeing the harvesting, grading and packaging of fish, oysters and other aquatic stock,Organising the sale, purchase and transportation of fish stock,Maintaining and evaluating records of farming activities, monitoring market activity and planning production accordingly,Managing business capital including budgeting, taxation, debt and loan management,May select, train and supervise staff and contractors
Core Skills: knowledge of fish biology including nutrition, diseases and breeding cycles, cleaning tanks, maintaining equipment, minor repairs, sampling water and analysing data
Certifications (External): SFI50119: Diploma of Aquaculture, SFI40219: Certificate IV in Seafood Post Harvest Operations, AHC52122: Diploma of Permaculture, Certificate of Aquaculture, Best Aquaculture Practices (BAP) certification, Aquaculture Stewardship Council (ASC) certification
Technologies: Recirculating Aquaculture Systems (RAS), offshore cage farming, biofloc technology, IoT devices, AI tools, underwater cameras
Soft Skills: Communication, adaptability, attention to detail, teamwork, problem-solving

Definition: A crop farmer grows plants for food, animal feed, fuel, or industrial use, managing all steps from soil preparation and planting to watering, fertilizing, and harvesting.
Career Pathway: Crop Farmer, Agricultural Crop Farm Manager, Crop Management Consultant
Competencies: Planning and coordinating the production and marketing of crops, such as grain, cotton, sugar cane, fruit and nuts, vegetables, turf and flowers, from soil preparation to harvest taking into account environmental and market factors,Selecting and planting seeds, seedlings and bulbs, and grafting new varieties to root stocks,Maintaining crop production by cultivating, de-budding and pruning, and maintaining optimal growing conditions,Organising and conducting farming operations, such as collecting, storing, grading and packaging produce, and organising the sale, purchase and despatch of produce,Directing and overseeing general farming activities such as fertilising and pest and weed control,Maintaining farm buildings, fences, equipment and water supply systems,Maintaining and evaluating records of farming activities, monitoring market activity, and planning crop preparation and production to meet contract requirements and market demand,Managing business capital including budgeting, taxation, debt and loan management,May select, train and supervise staff and contractors
Core Skills: Soil testing and nutrient management, Irrigation system operation, Pest and weed control methods, Crop rotation and yield optimisation, Farm machinery operation and maintenance
Certifications (External): Certified Professional Agronomist, Certified Crop Advisor, Organic Certification, GLOBALG.A.P. Certification, Regenerative Organic Certified, Accredited Agricultural Consultant
Technologies: Precision agriculture, GPS technology, Drones/UAS, Robotics/Automation, Variable-rate technology (VRT), Remote sensing, AI-driven crop recognition
Soft Skills: Communication, Problem-Solving, Adaptability, Collaboration, Teamwork

Definition: Livestock farmers raise animals such as beef cattle, dairy cows, and poultry for meat, milk, and egg production, managing their feeding, nutrition, and health.
Career Pathway: Farm Hand, Assistant Livestock Manager, Livestock Manager, Owner/Operator
Competencies: Breeding and raising livestock for the production of honey, meat, milk, skins, eggs and wool,Monitoring and maintaining the health and condition of livestock,Providing pastures and fodder to maintain appropriate nutritional levels,Moving livestock to optimise feeding opportunities,Organising and conducting farming operations such as catching, drenching and milking livestock, sterilising machines, and collecting, grading and packaging produce,Directing and overseeing general farming activities such as maintaining pens, sheds and cages, fertilising, controlling pests and weeds, and growing fodder,Maintaining fences, equipment and water supply systems,Organising the sale, purchase and transportation of livestock and produce,Maintaining and evaluating records of farming activities, monitoring market activity and planning production accordingly,Managing business capital including budgeting, taxation, debt and loan management,May select, train and supervise staff and contractors
Core Skills: Animal restraint, Taking and evaluating vital signs, Basic wound care, Ruminant hoof care, Calculate dosages of vaccines, dewormers, and antibiotics
Certifications (External): Diploma of Agribusiness Management, Diploma of Agriculture, Certificate III in Agriculture, G.A.P. Certification, Organic Certification, Beef Quality Assurance (BQA) Certification, Certificate IV in Agribusiness
Technologies: Imaging technology, Autonomous drone technology, Probiotic supplements, Non-invasive spectroscopy technology, Robotics, IoT (Internet of Things), Sexed semen
Soft Skills: Communication, Problem-Solving, Adaptability, Teamwork, Dependability

Definition: Mixed Crop and Livestock Farmers combine crop cultivation and livestock rearing on the same farm.
Career Pathway: Farm Hand, Assistant Farmer/Rancher, Farmer/Rancher, Farm Manager/Agricultural Manager
Competencies: Planning and coordinating the production and marketing of crops and livestock,Breeding and raising livestock for the production of meat, wool, skins, milk or eggs, and growing grain, seed crops, vegetables, fruit or nuts,Monitoring and maintaining the health and condition of livestock,Providing pastures and fodder to maintain appropriate nutritional levels,Selecting and purchasing seed for planting, planning and implementing breeding programs,Directing and overseeing general farming activities such as fertilising, and pest and weed control,Maintaining farm buildings, fences, equipment and water supply systems,Organising the sale, purchase and transportation of livestock and produce,Maintaining and evaluating records of farming activities, monitoring market activity and planning production accordingly,Managing business capital, monitoring market activity and planning production accordingly,May select, train and supervise staff and contractors
Core Skills: Soil Science and Nutrient Management, Precision Agriculture & Technology Integration, Pest Management, Cropping Systems and Plant Science, Agricultural Equipment Operation and Maintenance
Certifications (External): National Certificate: Mixed Farming Systems (NQF Level 2), Certificate IV in Agriculture AHC40122, Certificate I in Agriculture AHC10222, Good Agricultural Practices (GAP) Certification, Tractor Driver Certification, Occupational Certificate: Firefighting, Store and Control Agrochemical Products Effectively and Responsibly Certification
Technologies: Precision agriculture technology, Farm management software, Digital agriculture, Soil test kits, Cattle scanning systems, Drones, Autonomous tractors
Soft Skills: Creativity, Teamwork, Dependability, Problem-solving, Adaptability

Occupation: Advertising, Public Relations and Sales Manager
Definition: Plans, organizes, directs, controls and coordinates advertising, public relations, sales and marketing activities within organizations.
Career Pathway: Assistant Manager, Specialist Manager, Senior Manager, Director, Vice President
Competencies: Formulating and implementing policies and plans for advertising, public relations, sales and marketing in consultation with other managers,Directing the development of initiatives for new products, marketing and advertising campaigns,Organising and controlling sales activities by setting product mix, geographical sales areas and customer service standards,Directing merchandising methods and distribution policy by coordinating the work of salespersons, and organising agents and distributors,Directing sales methods and arrangements by setting prices and credit arrangements

Certifications (External): Google Skillshop, Certified Digital Marketing Professional (CDMP), Interactive Advertising Bureau (IAB) Digital Media Sales Certification, Certified Public Relations Leader (CPRL), Certified Public Relations Manager (CPRM), Certified Professional Sales Person (CPSP), Certified Professional Sales Leader (CPSL)
Technologies: Ad Campaign Management and Optimization, Media Monitoring and Analysis, Customer Relationship Management (CRM) software, Analytics software, Press Release Distribution tools, Social Media software

Definition: Corporate Services Managers plan, organise, direct, control and coordinate the overall administration of organisations.
Career Pathway: Administration Officer, Business Services Officer, Administration Manager, Business Services Manager, Corporate Services Manager, Corporate Services Director
Competencies: Providing high level administrative, strategic planning and operational support, research and advice to senior management on administrative matters such as staff management, financial planning, facility management and information services,Developing and managing the organisation's administrative, financial, physical and staff resources,Developing and implementing administrative, financial and operational procedural statements and guidelines for use by staff in the organisation,Analysing complex resource management issues and initiatives that affect the organisation, and preparing associated reports, correspondence and submissions,Providing information and support for the preparation of financial reports and budgets,Leading, managing and developing administrative staff to ensure smooth business operations and the provision of accurate and timely information,Representing the organisation in negotiations, and at conventions, seminars, public hearings and forums, and promoting existing and new programs and policies

Certifications (External): Certified Manager (CM), Certified Public Accountant (CPA), Project Management Professional (PMP), Certified Facilities Manager (CFM), Certificate IV in Business Administration, Diploma of Business (Operational Excellence), Diploma of Leadership and Management

Soft Skills: Communication skills, Critical thinking skills, Conflict-resolution skills, Adaptability, Delegation skills

Definition: Financial managers are responsible for the financial health of an organization, creating reports, directing investment activities, and developing long-term financial plans.
Career Pathway: Staff Accountant or Financial Analyst, Financial Controller or Internal Auditor, Financial Manager or Bank Manager or Credit Manager, City Comptroller or City Treasurer
Competencies: Determining, implementing, monitoring, reviewing and evaluating budgetary and accounting strategies, policies and plans in consultation with other managers,Providing financial information and interpreting the implications for business performance and funding needs,Coordinating the development, implementation and monitoring of accounting systems,Directing the preparation of financial reports summarising and forecasting the organisation's financial position such as income statements, balance sheets and analyses of future earnings and income,Assessing capital finance proposals and the financial status of operational projects,Advising on investment strategies, sources of funds and the distribution of earnings,Delivering long range profit forecasts, budgeting and financial reporting,Ensuring compliance with financial legislation and standards

Certifications (External): Certified Financial Planner (CFP®), Chartered Financial Analyst (CFA®), Certified Management Accountant (CMA), Master Financial Planner (MFP), Chartered Financial Manager (ChFM), Certificate IV in Business Finance, Diploma of Financial Management
Technologies: Financial planning software, CRM, portfolio management, risk assessment, data analytics, digital platforms, mobile apps
Soft Skills: Communication, Critical Thinking, Problem-Solving, Ethical Judgment, Adaptability

Definition: Human resources managers plan, coordinate, and direct the administrative functions of an organization, overseeing recruiting, interviewing, and hiring of new staff; consulting with top executives on strategic planning; and serving as a link between management and employees.
Career Pathway: Human Resources Assistant, HR Generalist, Senior HRBP, Head of HR, CHRO
Competencies: Determining, implementing, monitoring, reviewing and evaluating human resource management strategies, policies and plans to meet business needs,Advising and assisting other managers in applying sound recruitment and selection practices, and appropriate induction, training and development programs,Developing and implementing performance management systems to plan, appraise and improve individual and team performance,Representing the organisation in negotiations with unions and employees to determine remuneration and other conditions of employment,Developing and implementing occupational health and safety programs and equal employment opportunity programs, and ensuring compliance with related statutory requirements,Overseeing the application of redundancy and other employee retrenchment policies,Monitoring employment costs and productivity levels,May train and advise other managers in personnel and workplace relations matters

Certifications (External): SHRM Certified Professional (SHRM-CP), SHRM Senior Certified Professional (SHRM-SCP), Global Professional in Human Resources (GPHR), Professional in Human Resources (PHR), Certified HR Practitioner (CPHR), BSB40420 Certificate IV in Human Resource Management, Diploma of Human Resource Management

Soft Skills: Communication and Interpersonal Skills, Critical Thinking and Problem-Solving, Ethical Judgment and Integrity, Organizational and Time Management Skills, Active listening

Definition: Policy and Planning Managers plan, organise, direct, control and coordinate policy advice and strategic planning within organisations.
Career Pathway: Research Assistant, Policy Analyst, Policy Manager, Development Director, Chief Executive and Managing Director
Competencies: Developing, implementing and monitoring strategic plans, programs, policies, processes, systems and procedures to achieve goals, objectives and work standards,Developing, implementing, administering and participating in policy research and analysis,Coordinating the implementation of policies and practices,Establishing activity measures and measurements of accountability,Overseeing and participating in the development of policy documents and reports,Consulting with and providing expert advice to government officials and board members on policy, program and legislative issues,Representing the organisation in negotiations, and at conventions, seminars, public hearings and forums convened to discuss policy issues

Certifications (External): Master of Public Policy (MPP), Certified Public Policy Analyst (CPPA), Graduate Certificate in Public Policy, Chartered Policy Analyst (ChPA), Strategic Management Professional (SMP), Strategic Planning Professional (SPP), Certified Manager (CM)
Technologies: Geographic Information Systems (GIS), Policy analysis software, Statistical analysis software, Project management software, Data visualization tools, Risk assessment software, Database management systems

Definition: Research and Development Managers manage and direct R&D programs to meet organizational needs and develop potential new products.
Career Pathway: Research Assistant/Technician, Entry Level Research and Development, Research and Development Manager, Director of R&D, Vice President of R&D
Competencies: Determining, implementing and monitoring research and development strategies, policies and plans,Developing and implementing research projects, priorities and targets to support commercial and policy developments,Leading major research projects and coordinating activities of other research workers,Assessing the benefits and monitoring the costs and effectiveness of research and development activities,Interpreting results of research projects and recommending associated product and service development innovations,Providing advice on research and development options available to the organisation,Monitoring leading-edge developments in relevant disciplines and assessing implications for the organisation,May publish results of significant research projects

Definition: Construction managers oversee building projects, ensuring they are completed safely, on time, and within budget.

Competencies: Interpreting architectural drawings and specifications,Coordinating labour resources, and procurement and delivery of materials, plant and equipment,Consulting with architects, engineering professionals and other professionals, and technical and trades workers,Negotiating with building owners, property developers and subcontractors involved in the construction process to ensure projects are completed on time and within budget,Preparing tenders and contract bids,Operating and implementing coordinated work programs for sites,Ensuring adherence to building legislation and standards of performance, quality, cost and safety,Arranging submission of plans to local authorities,Building under contract, or subcontracting specialised building services,Overseeing the standard and progress of subcontractors' work,Arranging building inspections by local authorities

Definition: Engineering Managers lead teams and oversee the design, implementation, and refinement of product development and manufacturing processes, while also managing staff, resource allocation, and project logistics.

Definition: They plan, organize, direct, control, and coordinate the operations of importing, exporting, and wholesaling establishments.
Career Pathway: Import/Export Assistant, Coordinator, Manager, Director
Competencies: Identifying local and overseas business opportunities,Developing and implementing business plans, and marketing, operating, human resource, pricing and credit policies and procedures,Determining the mix of products and services to be provided and negotiating conditions of trade,Liaising with local and overseas suppliers and distributors about orders and products,Researching regulatory and statutory requirements affecting the importing, exporting, wholesaling and distribution of goods,Monitoring business performance and preparing estimates, financial statements and reports of operations,Appointing agents and distributors,Arranging the shipping of goods into and out of the country,Overseeing the display and sale of merchandise and preparation of product information for customer service staff and customers,Implementing after-sales service procedures

Core Skills: Assessment and Evaluation, Treatment Planning and Implementation, Knowledge of Anatomy and Physiology, Assistive Technology and Adaptive Equipment Use, Comfort with technology
Certifications (External): Certified Hand Specialist (CHT), Certified Autism Specialist (CAS), Board Certification in Gerontology (BCG), Certified Driving Rehabilitation Specialist (CDRS), Board Certification in Pediatrics (BCP)

Soft Skills: Empathy and Compassion, Adaptability and Flexibility, Problem-Solving and Critical Thinking, Collaboration and Teamwork, Clear communication skills

Definition: Physiotherapists help injured or ill people improve movement and manage pain and are often an important part of preventive care, rehabilitation, and treatment for patients with chronic conditions, illnesses, or injuries.
Career Pathway: Physiotherapist (Band 5), Senior Physiotherapist (Band 6), Advanced Clinical Practitioner/Specialist, Service Manager/Self-Employed/Research
Competencies: Administering muscle, nerve, joint and functional ability tests to identify and assess physical problems of patients,Designing treatment programs to address patients' problems,Treating patients to reduce pain, improve circulation, strengthen muscles, improve cardiothoracic, cardiovascular and respiratory functions, restore joint mobility, and improve balance and coordination,Using the therapeutic properties of exercise, heat, cold, massage, manipulation, hydrotherapy, electrotherapy, ultraviolet and infra-red light and ultrasound in the treatment of patients,Reviewing, continually monitoring, assessing and evaluating programs and treatments,Consulting with other health professionals as required about patients' problems, needs and progress,Instructing patients and their families in procedures to be continued at home,Recording treatments given and patients' responses and progress,Developing and implementing screening and preventative health promotion programs
Core Skills: Advanced Anatomy and Physiology Mastery, Evidence-Based Practice and Research Integration, Comprehensive Assessment and Diagnostic Skills, Anatomy, Clinical Skills
Certifications (External): Cardiovascular and Pulmonary Clinical Specialist (CCS), Clinical Electrophysiology Specialist, Geriatric Clinical Specialist (GCS), Neurologic Clinical Specialist (NCS), Oncology Specialist, Orthopaedic Clinical Specialist, Pediatric Clinical Specialist, Sports Clinical Specialist
Technologies: Wearable devices, Virtual reality (VR), TeleRehabilitation, Sensory Rehabilitation Technology, Robotic Physical Therapy Treatments, Artificial intelligence, Augmented reality
Soft Skills: Empathy, assertiveness, communication skills, compassion, critical thinking

Definition: Podiatrists provide medical and surgical care for people with foot, ankle, and lower leg problems.
Career Pathway: Residency Training, Associate Podiatrist/Clinic Staff Podiatrist, Private Practice/Group Practice Partner, Subspecialty Fellowship/Certification, Leadership/Academic Role
Competencies: Examining patients' feet to determine the nature and extent of conditions, deformities and injuries,Examining and treating foot disabilities caused by diseases such as diabetes, peripheral vascular disorders, rheumatoid arthritis and other neuropathies,Prescribing and arranging the fabrication of footwear to correct foot abnormalities,Performing minor surgery to remove and improve abnormal conditions,Prescribing and fitting replaceable pads, palliative and functional supports and other devices for the protection and correction of foot abnormalities,Advising patients about continued treatment and foot care,May provide rehabilitation services to the physically handicapped,May refer patients to or have patients referred from medical practitioners
Core Skills: suturing techniques, sterile techniques, fixation techniques, instrumentation, proper tissue handling
Certifications (External): Board Certification in Podiatric Orthopedics and Primary Podiatric Medicine, Foot and Ankle Surgery Certification, Certified Wound Specialist, Minimally Invasive Foot And Ankle Surgery, Limb Preservation and Salvage, Prevention and Treatment of Diabetic Foot Wounds, Fellowship of the Faculty of Podiatric Medicine within the RCPSG [FFPM RCPS (Glasg)]
Technologies: 3D Printing for Custom Orthotics, AI in Diagnosis, Robotic-Assisted Surgery, Digital Gait Analysis, Wearable Technology, Ultrasound Diagnostics, Podiatry EMR/EHR Software
Soft Skills: enjoy working with people, communication skills, patience, compassion, critical-thinking skills

Definition: These professionals diagnose and treat hearing, balance, speech, language, and swallowing disorders.
Career Pathway: Entry-Level Clinician, Specialized Clinician/Private Practice Owner/Researcher/Educator/Sales or Leadership Roles
Competencies: Administering and interpreting a wide range of audiometric tests to determine hearing efficiency and locate sites of detected hearing problems,Interpreting audiometric test results alongside other medical, social and behavioural diagnostic data,Evaluating total response pattern and acoustic tests to distinguish between organic and non-organic hearing loss,Planning, directing and participating in counselling, speech reading and other rehabilitation programs,Prescribing appropriate hearing aids and instructing patients in use,Administering tests and observing patients to determine nature and extent of disorders,Planning and conducting programs of remedial exercise to correct disorders such as stuttering and abnormal articulation,Administering individual and group therapy for rehabilitation of patients with communication problems caused by defective hearing, cerebral palsy, surgery and injury,Advising on treatment for children with difficulties in learning to speak,Counselling and guiding language-handicapped individuals, their families, teachers and employers
Core Skills: determining range of hearing function, planning and conducting rehabilitation programs, fitting and adjustment of hearing aids or cochlear implants, auditory training, audiological counseling
Certifications (External): Certificate of Clinical Competence in Audiology (CCC-A), Certificate of Clinical Competence in Speech-Language Pathology (CCC-SLP), Certified Practising Membership with Speech Pathology Australia (SPA), Certified Member (Cert MRCSLT) from RCSLT (UK), Full Member from NZSLT (New Zealand), Full Member from IASLT (Ireland)

Occupation: General Practitioners and Resident Medical Officers
Definition: Diagnose, treat, and manage health conditions in primary or hospital care settings.
Career Pathway: Medical Doctor, Registrar, Physician, General Practitioner, Medical Officer, Associate Medical Director, Medical Director
Competencies: Conducting examinations and questioning patients to determine the nature of disorders and illnesses, and recording patients' medical information,Ordering laboratory tests, x-rays and other diagnostic procedures, and interpreting findings to assist in diagnosis,Providing overall care for patients, and prescribing and administering treatments, medications and other remedial measures,Monitoring patients' progress and response to treatment,Advising on diet, exercise and other habits which aid prevention and treatment of disease and disorders,Referring patients to, and exchanging medical information with, specialist medical practitioners,Reporting births, deaths and notifiable diseases to government authorities,Arranging the admission of patients to hospitals

Certifications (External): RACGP Fellowship, ACRRM Fellowship, Standard pathway (for IMGs), Competent Authority pathway (for IMGs), Specialist pathway (for IMGs)
Technologies: Electronic Health Records (EHRs), Telemedicine/Telehealth, Voice-assistant technology, Mobile apps, Digital Health Record, Remote Patient Monitoring, Simulation equipment

Definition: Anaesthetists are specialist doctors responsible for providing anesthesia and pain management to patients before, during, and after operations and surgical procedures.
Career Pathway: Foundation year 1, Foundation year 2, Specialist training, Consultant Anaesthetist, Senior Consultant
Competencies: Performing pre-operative examinations of patients to determine appropriate anaesthetic and sedation in concurrence with internal medicine specialists and surgeons,Discussing the anaesthetic process with patients and obtaining their informed consent prior to surgery,Administering local, regional and general anaesthetics using a variety of methods such as inhalational and intravenous administration,Supervising the transfer of patients to operating theatres, positioning on operating tables, keeping patients warm, and responding quickly and accurately if any problems arise,Monitoring patients throughout surgical procedures and in immediate post-operative procedures,Recording details of anaesthetic and sedation administered, and the condition of patients before, during and after anaesthesia,Liaising with other health care workers to provide diagnosis and treatment for patients with chronic pain, and to diagnose and treat patients requiring intensive care or resuscitation,May instruct medical, nursing, student and ancillary staff on the signs, symptoms and diagnosis of allergic and anaphylactic reactions to anaesthetic agents, and supervision and treatment of life threatening emergencies

Certifications (External): Fellowship of the Australian and New Zealand College of Anaesthetists (FANZCA), ABA Certification, Clinician Educator Pathway, Exceptional Clinician Pathway, Research & Fellowship Pathway, Alternate Entry Path – Fellowship, Adult Cardiac Anesthesiology Certification

Definition: A physician specialist focuses on a specific area of medicine or a group of patients to diagnose, manage, prevent, or treat certain types of symptoms and conditions.
Career Pathway: Specialty Registrar, Specialty doctors, Associate specialist doctor, Consultants
Competencies: Examining patients to determine the nature and extent of problems after referral from general medical practitioners and other medical specialists, and undertaking laboratory tests and diagnostic procedures,Analysing test results and other medical information to make diagnoses,Prescribing and administering drugs, and remedial and therapeutic treatment and procedures,Recording medical information and data,Reporting specified contagious and notifiable diseases to government health and immigration authorities,May admit or refer patients to hospitals,May consult other medical specialists
Core Skills: Obtain and apply medical knowledge, Provide compassionate and effective medical care, Maintain comprehensive and timely medical records, Act in a consultative role to other physicians, Work effectively as a member of a health care team
Certifications (External): Critical Care Medicine, Hospice and Palliative Medicine, Neurocritical Care, Pain Medicine, Pediatric Anesthesiology, Sleep Medicine, Medical Toxicology

Definition: A psychiatrist is a medical doctor specializing in the diagnosis, treatment, and prevention of mental, emotional, and behavioral disorders.

Definition: A surgeon is a medical doctor who performs surgery.

Definition: Other Medical Practitioners is a group of specialist medical doctors including dermatologists, emergency medicine specialists, obstetricians and gynaecologists, ophthalmologists, pathologists, diagnostic and interventional radiologists, and radiation oncologists.

Competencies: Planning, designing, building, configuring and commissioning telecommunications devices, networks and systems, such as voice, radio, two-way, data, microwave, satellite and digital data systems, and ensuring telecommunications systems interconnect with equipment from different manufacturers, service providers and users,Compiling engineering project proposals to define goals, identify scope, background and need, and ascertain cost of equipment, parts and services,Evaluating and procuring new products and services from vendors,Ensuring compliance with laws, regulations, policies and procedures in the provision of telecommunications systems,Selecting and developing new telecommunications sites by locating sites, filing documents, drawing up documents for approval, drafting construction drawings and following through to approval,Determining appropriate configurations of telecommunications hardware and software, ensuring desired performance of telecommunications equipment,Preparing and interpreting specifications, drawings and regulations for the use of telecommunications equipment,Determining the type and arrangement of circuits, transformers, circuit-breakers, transmission lines and equipment,Identifying and analysing problems and needs of existing telecommunications systems, such as interference, intelligibility and clarity, to determine the most appropriate means of reducing, eliminating and avoiding current and future problems and improve communications,Monitoring telecommunications systems to assess need for updates, upgrades, enhancements, preventive maintenance and new systems,Assessing performance levels of system hardware and software to project future needs, and developing shortand long-terms plans for updating equipment, adding capabilities, enhancing existing systems and providing improved telecommunications

Definition: A barrister is a lawyer who specializes in court advocacy, litigation, and providing independent legal advice to clients, often hired by solicitors.
Career Pathway: Entry-level role in a law firm or law department, Level 6 Professional Higher Diploma in Law, The academic stage (undergraduate degree and law conversion), The vocational stage (Bar course), The pupillage/work-based learning stage (pupil barrister), Lead a team, Manager, King's Counsel (KC), Judge, Ombudsman
Competencies: Receiving written information in the form of briefs and verbal instructions concerning cases from solicitors, other specialist legal professionals and clients,Providing advice and written opinions on points of law,Conferring with clients and witnesses in preparation for court proceedings,Drawing up pleadings, affidavits and other court documents,Researching statutes and previous court decisions relevant to cases,Outlining the facts to the court, calling and questioning witnesses, and making addresses to the court to argue a client's case,Providing opinion on complex legal issues,May draw up or settle documents
Core Skills: Advocacy skills (oral and written), strong analytical and research abilities, experience in legal writing and drafting, advanced negotiation skills, effective analytical and evaluative skills
Certifications (External): Australian Practising Certificate, Specialist Accreditation in a particular field of law, International Bar Association (IBA) Membership, Chartered Institute of Arbitrators (CIArb) Fellowship, Australian Institute of Company Directors (AICD) Company Directors Course, Mediation and Dispute Resolution Certificate
Technologies: Case management solutions, Video conferencing, Online legal research tools, Cloud-based document storage, AI, E-discovery, Practice management software
Soft Skills: Excellent written and oral communication skills, confidence, tact and discretion, excellent organisational skills, ability to think on one's feet

Core Skills: Legal Research, Trial Preparation, Document Drafting, Case Management Software, Negotiation
Certifications (External): Practising certificate (Australia), Certified Legal Manager (CLM), Certified Paralegal (CP), Professional Paralegal (PP), Certified Information Privacy Professional (CIPP), Appellate Judicial Skills Certification, Civil Trial Law Certification
Technologies: AI-enabled workflow automation, legal research platforms, contract management software, data analytics, cloud-based applications, cybersecurity tools, eDiscovery
Soft Skills: Communication, critical thinking, integrity, organization, problem-solving

Definition: A solicitor is a qualified legal professional who provides specialist legal advice and represents a client's legal interests.

Definition: Metal Engineering Process Workers perform routine tasks in manufacturing metal products.

Competencies: Positioning and holding tools and metal products,Performing assembly and dismantling operations such as screwing and bolting,Operating power hammers, presses and other metal cutting and shaping tools and machines,Soldering and spot welding components using electrical spot and butt welding machines,Transporting tools, materials and work pieces to and from sites and workbenches,Cleaning and preparing working surfaces
Core Skills: Reading and interpreting technical drawings, mathematical and calculation skills, experience with fastening methods, operating metal cutting and shaping tools, soldering and spot welding components
Certifications (External): American Welding Society (AWS) certification, National Commission for the Certification of Crane Operators (NCCCO), National Center for Construction Education and Research (NCCER) rigging certifications, Institute for Printed Circuits soldering certification, Fabricators & Manufacturers Association (FMA) precision sheet metal work certification, ISO 9001, ASME Section IX
Technologies: Power hammers, presses, metal cutting and shaping tools, electrical spot and butt welding machines, computerized equipment, process control, emerging technologies
Soft Skills: Communication, Problem-Solving, Collaboration, Cooperation

Definition: Plastics and Rubber Factory Workers perform routine tasks in manufacturing plastic and rubber products.
Career Pathway: Factory Worker, Machine Operator, Shift Supervisor, Production Manager
Competencies: Dumping material into hoppers of machines,Stopping moulding machines and discharging contents,Cutting foam products from foam blocks,Cleaning, smoothing and waxing moulds for making products,Brushing and spraying release agents onto moulds to assist with the removal of moulded products,Building up layers of fibreglass and resin on moulds,Cleaning work areas, tools and equipment,May smooth rough edges of moulds using files, grinders and sanders

Certifications (External): Certified Manufacturing Associate (CMfgA), Certified Manufacturing Technologist (CMfgT), Certified Manufacturing Engineer (CMfgE), Lean Certification, Robotics in Manufacturing Fundamentals, Certificate II in Engineering, MSMWHS200 Work Safely
Technologies: Injection molding, blow molding, foaming, thermoforming, automated guided vehicles (AGVs), autonomous mobile robots (AMRs), robotics
Soft Skills: Problem-solving, Teamwork, Attention to detail, Communication, Adaptability

Definition: Product Quality Controllers ensure that products consistently conform to industry, company, and consumer expectations, aiming to minimize cost and maximize efficiency.
Career Pathway: Quality and Compliance Associate, Quality and Compliance Program Manager, Senior Quality and Compliance Program Manager
Competencies: Studying product specifications and taking measurements to determine conformity to specifications,Examining and marking output for visible defects such as cracks, holes and breakages,Making minor repairs and adjustments to products,Compiling quality assurance reports, maintaining documentation and reporting findings,Examining products for defects and grading produce,Designating grading of produce and recording details of assessments according to classification system,Collecting and labelling samples for inspection,Recording details of sampling procedures and sources of samples,Preparing samples and carrying out prescribed tests
Core Skills: Statistical Analysis, Testing and Inspection Techniques, Technical Writing, Automation Tools, Data Analysis
Certifications (External): Certified Manager of Quality/Organizational Excellence (CMQ/OE), Certified Quality Auditor (CQA), Certified Quality Engineer (CQE), ISO 9001:2015 Lead Auditor Certification, Lean Six Sigma Green Belt Certification, Certified Quality Improvement Associate (CQIA), Certified Pharmaceutical GMP Professional (CPGP)
Technologies: Quality Management System (QMS) software, Statistical Process Control (SPC) tools, Automated inspection systems, 3D scanning equipment, Artificial Intelligence, Machine learning, SCADA systems
Soft Skills: Problem-Solving, Attention to Detail, Effective Communication, Teamwork, Time Management

Definition: Timber and Wood Process Workers perform routine tasks in paper and pulp mills, sawmills, timber yards, and wood processing and timber products factories.
Career Pathway: Wood Processor, Lumber Grader, Sawmill Operator, Production Supervisor
Competencies: Rolling logs from trucks and conveyors to log decks, saw carriages and stacking bays,Placing logs and wood billets onto conveyors and lathes for processing into chips, veneers and pulp,Sorting and stacking timber during milling,Placing timber for processing by machines and unloading cut timber from tail end of machines,Assisting with setting up and operating plant and ancillary equipment used in the manufacture of sheets and boards,Transporting processed wood products, such as plywood, chipboard sheets and panels, to work areas,Clearing blockages in machines,Assisting with measuring and cutting materials,Packing and loading finished products for transportation,Cleaning work areas, tools and equipment
Core Skills: Operating sawmill machinery, Sorting/stacking/grading timber, Trimming timber, Recording timber sizes/grades/amount, Basic maintenance on machinery
Certifications (External): Forest Stewardship Council (FSC), Australian Forestry Standard (AFS), Responsible Wood, Programme for the Endorsement of Forest Certification (PEFC), Sustainable Forestry Initiative (SFI), FWP40216 Certificate IV in Timber Processing
Technologies: Sawmill machinery, log loaders, forklifts, timber saw, circular saw, planer, band saw, ERP and production planning systems (Meka)
Soft Skills: Problem-solving, teamwork, communication, ability to work under pressure

Definition: This occupation includes roles such as Cement and Concrete Plant Workers, Chemical Plant Workers, Clay Processing Factory Workers, Fabric and Textile Factory Workers, and Recycling Workers.
Career Pathway: Factory Worker, Quality Control Inspector, Production Supervisor, Production Planner, Supply Chain Manager
Competencies: Performs routine tasks in manufacturing cement and concrete products such as greasing and assembling concrete moulds, holding reinforcing steel in position during concrete pours, stripping moulds from dried concrete products, and finishing products,Performs routine tasks in a chemical processing plant such as delivering materials to processing areas, dumping ingredients into hoppers, operating machines to heat, cool and agitate chemical solutions, filling and fastening covers on containers, and attaching labels and information on products,Performs routine tasks in manufacturing clay and ceramic products such as loading clay into machines, stacking products on kiln cars, pallets and trolleys, and moving kiln cars and trolleys to and from kilns, dryers, sorting, storage and shipping areas,Performs routine tasks in a fabric and textile factory such as cutting canvas, upholstery and curtain fabrics, delivering materials to machines, operating automatic machines using computerised patterns, pressing partially completed and finished garments, and inspecting and finishing completed garments ,Performs routine tasks in manufacturing footwear such as basic hand cutting of shoe components, delivering materials to machines, and inspecting and finishing completed footwear,Performs routine tasks in manufacturing glassware such as setting up, adjusting and repairing automatic machines and equipment, and checking weight of glassware,Performs routine tasks in tanning and finishing leather, hides and skins such as fleshing hides by cutting out pieces of flesh and fat, laying out hides and skins for classing and drying and arranging heaters to dry them, spraying dried hides with preservatives, and treating, pressing and securing hides and skins
Core Skills: Manufacturing processes, Quality control, Equipment diagnosis, Data analysis, Problem solving
Certifications (External): Certified Production Technician (CPT) 4.0, Certified Logistics Technician (CLT) 4.0, Certified Forklift Technician (CFT), Certified Technician-Supply Chain Automation (CT-SCA), Certified Manufacturing Associate (CMfgA), Certified Manufacturing Technologist (CMfgT)
Technologies: Automation, Robotics, IoT sensors, Augmented Reality (AR) headsets, Artificial Intelligence (AI), Digital twins, Predictive maintenance
Soft Skills: Teamwork, Communication Skills, Problem Solving, Adaptability, Professionalism

Definition: Aquaculture Workers perform routine tasks in breeding and raising fish and other aquatic stock.
Career Pathway: Hatchery Technician, Farm Technician, Aquaculture Manager, Senior Aquaculture Manager
Competencies: Feeding and grading fish, and monitoring their growth,Assisting with farm layout and constructing nets, long-lines and cages,Checking and looking after equipment and fish housing,Operating pumps and other equipment,Testing and checking on water quality,Removing dead and dying fish,Operating lifting equipment such as forklifts and small cranes,Harvesting fish, and sorting and packing for transportation,Restocking pens, pools, tanks, ponds, rivers and dams with juvenile fish,Collecting and recording growth, production and water quality data
Core Skills: Water quality management, Breeding and hatchery management, Data collection and analysis, Water chemistry, Feed management
Certifications (External): Best Aquaculture Practices (BAP), GLOBALG.A.P. IFA – Aquaculture Certification, Aquaculture Science Certificate, Fisheries and Aquaculture Techniques Certificate, Florida Aquaculture Association Certification
Technologies: Water pump control, Temperature control, Recirculating Aquaculture System (RAS), Aquaculture software, Water Quality Tracking, Smart Monitoring and Automation, Feed and Nutrition Management
Soft Skills: A desire to make a difference, passion for animal welfare, dedication, eagerness to learn

Definition: Crop Farm Workers plant, inspect, and harvest crops, and operate and service farm machinery and tools.
Career Pathway: Farmworker/Laborer, Senior Farmworker, Crew Leader/Supervisor, Agricultural Manager/Farmer
Competencies: Planting trees, seeds, seedlings, roots, bulbs, vines and other plants using hand tools and farm machines,Building trellises for climbing vegetables and vines,Operating farm machines to cultivate, fertilise, spray and harvest fruit, nuts, grains and vegetables,Spraying trees, vines and other plants with chemicals to control weed growth, insects, fungus growth and diseases,Thinning, weeding and hoeing row crops, and pruning trees and vines,Irrigating land for crop growth,Selecting and picking fruit, nuts, grains and vegetables according to size and ripeness, and discarding rotting and over-ripened produce,Grading, sorting, bunching and packing produce into containers,Loading filled fruit, nut, grain and vegetable containers onto trucks
Core Skills: machinery operation, forklift knowledge, irrigation knowledge, crop production experience, mechanical skills
Certifications (External): Certified Crop Adviser (CCA), Certified Professional Agronomist, Certified Agricultural Irrigation Specialist, Certificate I in Agriculture, Certificate IV in Agriculture, Accredited Farm Manager, Landscape Industry Certified Horticultural Technician
Technologies: GPS-guided tractors, autonomous equipment, drones for crop monitoring, smart irrigation systems, farm management software, sensor technology, soil testing equipment
Soft Skills: Communication, organization, teamwork, dependability, adaptability

Definition: Forestry and Logging Workers perform routine tasks in cultivating and maintaining forests, and logging, felling, and sawing trees.
Career Pathway: Grounds worker, Choke setter, Bucker, Faller, Cutter operator, Feller buncher operator, Climbing Arborist
Competencies: Maintaining forest roads, buildings, facilities, signs and equipment,Killing weeds, felling and de-barking non-productive trees and thinning young plantations,Collecting seeds, and cultivating and planting seedlings for reafforestation purposes,Applying fertilisers, insecticides and herbicides to individual trees and general forest areas,Maintaining look-out for fires in forests,Removing major branches and tree tops, trimming branches and sawing trunks into logs,Assisting with loading and transporting logs,Planning the felling of trees and determining the natural and intended fall of each tree,Clearing surrounding area of saplings and debris prior to tree-felling,Operating and maintaining manual and machine saws to fell trees and to cut felled trees into logs
Core Skills: Operating chainsaws, Operating mechanical logging equipment, Measuring timber, Assessing harvest areas, Applying herbicides
Certifications (External): First Aid and CPR Certification, Forest Stewardship Council (FSC), Responsible Wood (Australian Forestry Standard), SFI Forest Management Certification, FSC Chain of Custody Certification
Technologies: Geographic Information Systems (GIS), Drones and Unmanned Aerial Vehicles (UAVs), LiDAR (Light Detection and Ranging), Remote Sensing and Satellite Data, Automated tools (robotic tree planters, autonomous vehicles), Mechanical equipment
Soft Skills: Communication, teamwork, adaptability, attention to detail

Competencies: Patrolling, inspecting and reporting on the condition of livestock,Providing livestock with feed and water,Assisting with maintaining the health and welfare of livestock,Mustering and droving livestock to milking and shearing sheds and between paddocks to ensure sufficient feed is available,Washing and cleaning udders, and attaching milking machines to udders and milking cows,Collecting eggs and placing in incubators,Herding sheep for shearing and keeping mobs separate during shearing,Spreading fleeces on skirting tables for classing, pressing wool and branding bales,Exercising horses by walking, riding, leading and swimming, and attending to horses at track work, barrier trials and races,Cleaning stables and hatcheries, storing bedding and performing minor repairs on fixtures, buildings and fences,Assembling, preparing and storing horse gear

Certification

Definition: A rheumatologist is a physician specializing in the diagnosis and treatment of arthritis and other diseases of the joints, muscles, and bones.
Career Pathway: Fellow, Associate, Senior Associate, Partner/Director, Department Head
Competencies: Diagnoses and manages autoimmune, inflammatory and musculoskeletal disorders.,Conducts comprehensive joint, tendon and soft-tissue examinations.,Interprets laboratory tests such as ANA, RF, anti-CCP, ESR, CRP and other autoimmune markers.,Interprets imaging including X-ray, MRI and musculoskeletal ultrasound.,Performs joint aspiration and therapeutic joint or soft-tissue injections.,Develops long-term treatment plans for chronic rheumatic conditions including DMARDs and biologic therapies.,Monitors treatment response, disease activity and medication side effects.,Coordinates multidisciplinary care with physiotherapists, immunologists, orthopaedic surgeons and primary care providers.,Educates patients on disease progression, lifestyle modifications and self-management strategies.,Maintains detailed clinical records, research documentation and ongoing patient management plans.,Participates in clinical research, evidence-based practice updates and continuous medical education.,May supervise junior doctors, nurses, or researchers in clinical rheumatology settings.

Technologies: EMR/EHR software, CyTOF mass cytometry, Remote Patient Monitoring, Biologic Therapy Tracking Software, MRI, scintigraphy, PET

Definition: A cardiothoracic surgeon is a physician who specializes in surgical procedures of the heart, lungs, esophagus, and other organs in the chest.

Competencies: Loads the digester with raw materials and chemicals.,Regulates and adjusts the temperature and pressure within the digester.,Tests samples by titration or standard colour test to determine completion of process.,Drains liquid from digester and monitors the removal of the cooked pulp.,Takes samples of bleached material for laboratory testing.,Washes bleached material and blends to obtain uniform quality.,May be required to add chemicals during the bleaching process and complete chemical or electrolytic tests.,Undertakes the addition of size, fillers, dyes, alum and chemicals, and tests for correct consistency.,Ensures transfer of completed batch to storage tanks where it is kept under agitation to maintain consistency.,May mix and cook colouring matter for dyeing product in the machine.,Controls flow of wet pulp through rotary screens to paper making machines.,Operates drier and calendar rollers.,Operates super-calendar to impart gloss and finish to surface of paper.,Operates machine to glaze or impregnate paper with coating mixture.,Separates sheets from felts and lays sheets in packs, re-presses packs.,Separates sheets from pack and dries.
Core Skills: operating pulp and paper-making machinery, using computer-controlled systems, testing quality of pulp and paper, conducting titration tests, inspecting paper visually
Certifications (External): MSM30116 Cert III in Process Manufacturing
Technologies: Process control systems, quality control sensors, computerized maintenance management systems (CMMS), distributed control systems (DCS), laboratory testing equipment, automated material handling, programmable logic controllers (PLCs)
Soft Skills: Safety Focus, Attention to Detail, Machine Operation, Problem-Solving, Process Monitoring

Definition: Railway Signal Operators control the movement of trains, and assemble and disassemble trains within a marshalling yard.
Career Pathway: Railway Signal Operator, Signalling Supervisor, Control Room Manager
Competencies: Directs trains within marshalling yards.,Breaks apart and join train wagons and carriages.,Places wagons, carriages and engines into sidings.,Directs outgoing trains to the main line.,May conduct safety checks.
Core Skills: Verbal comprehension, communication skills, reasoning skills, basic math, attention to detail
Certifications (External): Rail Signalling Cert, Rail Safety Worker
Technologies: Block signalling, Centralized traffic control (CTC), Interlocking systems, Cab signalling, European Rail Traffic Management System (ERTMS), Dispatching software, Communication Based Train Control (CBTC)
Soft Skills: Attention to Detail, Safety Focus, Decision-Making, Composure Under Pressure, Problem-Solving

Definition: Train Controllers are responsible for the safe direction of all train movements and maintaining "On Time" running for passengers.
Career Pathway: Trainee Train Controller, Train Controller, Senior Train Controller, Chief Train Controller, Operations Manager
Competencies: Authorises and direct movements of trains.,Communicates with locomotive engineers to ensure safe movements of trains.,Familiarises themselves with the weight, length and schedules of trains.,Records movement of trains including departures and scheduled stops.,Provides other train controllers with information on trains progress.,Authorises and controls any activity taking place on railway tracks, including maintenance work.,Contacts relevant personal to deal with faults or mechanical failures.,Reports any accidents or incidents to the land transport authority and any other relevant body such as emergency services.
Core Skills: Ability to interpret information from multiple sources, knowledge of railway operations, ability to operate a trunked radio system, analytical approach to problem solving, ability to plan program and direct operations staff
Certifications (External): Rail Operations Controller Cert, Transportation Safety
Technologies: European Train Control System, Driver Machine Interface, Balise Transmission Module, Odometric sensors, 5G Technology, Virtualization, Containerization, On-Board Automatic Train Control
Soft Skills: Decision-Making Under Pressure, Attention to Detail, Safety Focus, Problem-Solving, Communication

Occupation: Waste Water and Water Plant Operators
Definition: Water and wastewater treatment plant operators manage machines to transfer or treat water or wastewater, including collecting and testing samples and adding chemicals to disinfect.
Industry: Electricity, Gas, Water and Waste Services
Career Pathway: Entry-Level Operator, Certified Operator (Higher Level License), Specialized Operator, Supervisory/Management Position, Plant Operations Oversight/Staff Management
Competencies: Controls flow of raw water into plant, by regulating electric motors, pumps and valves.,Adds specified amounts of chemicals and activates agitators to mix chemicals. carries out such tests as are required in accordance with training given.,Allows impurities to settle and removes them by filtering water through filtering material.,Pumps purified water into mains, monitors flow and distribution.,Cleans tanks and maintains equipment, and makes minor repairs.,Pumps waste water into oxidation/settling ponds.,Removes sludge.,Burns off gases, treats and discharges waste water when it reaches the required levels of purity.
Core Skills: Operate, monitor, and maintain wastewater treatment equipment and systems, routine water quality testing, adjust chemical dosing and treatment processes, perform preventive maintenance on mechanical and electrical components, calibrate instruments and troubleshoot malfunctions using SCADA or similar systems
Certifications (External): NWP30222 Cert III in Water Industry Operations
Technologies: SCADA, AI-powered platforms, chemical feed pumps, streaming current detectors, automated jar testing, pressure and flow sensors, filtration technology
Soft Skills: Safety Focus, Attention to Detail, Problem-Solving, Environmental Awareness, Process Monitoring

Core Skills: Storytelling Principles, Screenplay Formatting, Scene Construction, Developing Characters, Pacing
Certifications (External): Advanced Diploma of Professional Screenwriting (RMIT), Advanced Diploma of Professional Screenwriting (10678NAT), Screenwriting: Film and TV Comprehensive Certificate Program (UCLA Extension)
Technologies: Final Draft, Celtx, Fade In, Arc Studio, WriterDuet, Highland 2, Kit Scenarist
Soft Skills: Creativity, Storytelling, Critical Thinking, Patience, Discipline

Definition: Special effects artists and animators create two- and three-dimensional models, images that appear to move, and visual effects for television, movies, video games, and other forms of media.
Career Pathway: Junior Animator, Animator, Senior Animator, Lead Animator, Animation Director
Competencies: Character design, creating visually appealing and expressive characters, Storyboarding, visualizing scenes and narrative flow, Keyframing, defining major movements and poses, Rendering, producing final animated output, Collaboration, working with teams like directors and sound designers.
Core Skills: Technical proficiency in animation software and tools, attention to detail, time management, problem-solving skills, storytelling abilities
Certifications (External): Diploma of 3D Design and Animation, Certificate III in Screen and Media (Animation), Diploma in Animation & Multimedia, Certificate in 3D Animation and VFX, Certificate in Game Art and Design, Certificate in Motion Graphics, Motion Graphics Certificate
Technologies: Autodesk Maya, Blender, Adobe After Effects, Houdini, Cinema 4D, Toon Boom Harmony, Adobe Photoshop
Soft Skills: Creativity, Patience, Attention to Detail, Problem-Solving, Artistic Vision

Definition: Environmental scientists collect, study, and report on data of air, food, water and other sources and then recommend action.
Career Pathway: Junior Environmental Scientist, Environmental Scientist, Senior Environmental Scientist, Project Manager, Environmental Consultant
Competencies: Determine data collection methods, Collect and compile environmental data samples, Analyze data to identify pollution sources/hazards, Recommend actions to protect environment/health, Write technical reports and present findings
Core Skills: Geospatial Technologies, Environmental Impact Assessment, Data Collection and Quality, Chemical analysis, Sample collection & analysis
Certifications (External): Certified Environmental Scientist (CES), Environmental Professional In-Training (EPI), Qualified Environmental Professional (QEP), Certified Professional Geologist, Certified Professional Wetland Scientist, Certified Professional Environmental Auditor (CPEA), Certified Industrial Hygienist (CIH)
Technologies: GIS, statistical analysis software, electron beam technology, ArcGIS, Python, JavaScript, R
Soft Skills: Analytical Thinking, Problem-Solving, Communication, Attention to Detail, Data Interpretation

Definition: A Sustainability Analyst uses data to analyze environmental risks and develop strategies, policies, and recommendations to help organizations become more eco-friendly and socially responsible.
Career Pathway: Junior Sustainability Analyst, Sustainability Analyst, Senior Sustainability Consultant, Sustainability Manager, Chief Sustainability Officer
Competencies: Analyze environmental data and metrics, Develop and implement sustainability strategies and policies, Assess the environmental impact of business operations, Collaborate with internal and external stakeholders on initiatives, Monitor and report on progress towards sustainability goals
Core Skills: Data analysis, Auditing, Key Performance Indicators (KPIs), Research, Presentations
Certifications (External): Living Future Accreditation (LFA), Certified Climate Change Professional (CC-P), Certified Sustainable Development Professional, Sustainability Excellence Professional (SEP), Certified Sustainability and Resilience Professional, Certificate in ESG Investing, GECA Certification
Technologies: ESG software platforms, Data analytics tools, Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) software, Geographic Information Systems (GIS), Building energy modeling software, Carbon accounting tools, Renewable energy technologies
Soft Skills: Analytical Thinking, Strategic Thinking, Communication, Influence, Collaboration
